description: The application offers users a functionality to upload text files that are stored in the user's personal directory, users can then read uploaded files back. The application does not validate the upload path and the file type allowing the upload of dangerous files. Arbitrary code execution is possible if a file is uploaded to the web root and it is interpreted and executed as code (e.g. JSP) by the application server.
topics: Unrestricted Upload of File with Dangerous Type
title: Arbitrary File Upload
trophyDescription: The candidate is proficient in implementing secure file upload functionalities.

infoList.title: Starting the exercise
infoList.description: When starting the exercise you will be presented with an Ubuntu desktop. Wait for Eclipse IDE and Firefox to launch.

infoList.title: Eclipse
infoList.description: Switch to Eclipse, click on the "Servers" tab, then click on "Start the Server" to launch the application server.

infoList.title: Firefox
infoList.description: Switch to Firefox, browse to: http://www.vulnerableapp.com:8050 . Login to the Vulnerable Application using the following credentials: user / password

infoList.title: Finishing the exercise
infoList.description: When you have completed the exercise, browse to Running Exercises" and click on "Mark Completed". Provisional results will be available in the "History" tab.

infoList.title: Troubleshooting
infoList.description: Restore source code: if you accidentally break the app's functionality, you can reset the app to the original source code using the shell script at: /home/rtf/Desktop/RTF/restoreSource.sh

flagList.instructions: Remediate the class handlers.UploadHandler, preventing the manipulation of the upload directory and restricting uploaded files to be documents only.

hint.text: Whitelist the uploaded file extension to only accept "txt" files. Ensure the user can only upload files within his personal directory.

flagList.instructions: Manipulate the HTTP request to upload a JSP web shell into the Application Server's web root to achieve command execution on the server. Reference step-by-step instructions on the Exercise's Reference document.

resources.title: CWE-434: Unrestricted Upload of File with Dangerous Type
